<org.eclipse.epf.uma:TaskDescription xmi:version="2.0" xmlns:xmi="http://www.omg.org/XMI" xmlns:org.eclipse.epf.uma="http://www.eclipse.org/epf/uma/1.0.6/uma.ecore" xmlns:epf="http://www.eclipse.org/epf" epf:version="1.5.1" xmi:id="-4JVT-SswJXGyHAd6O7Mkow" name=",_cRNGIL-PEd2e1-cAeXIm5A" guid="-4JVT-SswJXGyHAd6O7Mkow" changeDate="2008-12-01T11:04:54.712+0100">
  <mainDescription>&lt;P class=MsoNormal style=&quot;MARGIN: 0cm 0cm 0pt&quot;>&lt;SPAN style=&quot;mso-ansi-language: EN-US&quot;>&lt;FONT size=3>&lt;FONT face=&quot;Times New Roman&quot;>In this task, strategic decisions are taken about the architecture to use in the composition. All the steps are similar for all the enterprises. There will be little differences depending on the company experience, which will help to carry out the task with better results. The results will be the different approaches to solve the problem: architectural options, patterns and policies.&lt;?xml:namespace prefix = o ns = &quot;urn:schemas-microsoft-com:office:office&quot; />&lt;o:p>&lt;/o:p>&lt;/FONT>&lt;/FONT>&lt;/SPAN>&lt;/P></mainDescription>
  <sections xmi:id="_UBUgP8HrEd2B2LAvnwDruw" name="Extract architectural needs from requirements " guid="_UBUgP8HrEd2B2LAvnwDruw">
    <sectionDescription>&lt;P>&lt;SPAN style=&quot;mso-ansi-language: EN-US&quot;>&lt;FONT size=3>&lt;FONT face=&quot;Times New Roman&quot;>The first step is to analyse the requirements, which will include all the information which is needed to take decisions concerning the different alternatives to solve the problem. The relevant requirements list obtained in a previous task could be very helpful to extract requirements which will guide the developers to identify all the alternatives. With this analysis, a first idea of architectural needs is obtained. &lt;?xml:namespace prefix = o ns = &quot;urn:schemas-microsoft-com:office:office&quot; />&lt;o:p>&lt;/o:p>&lt;/FONT>&lt;/FONT>&lt;/SPAN>&lt;/P>&#xD;
&lt;P class=MsoNormal style=&quot;MARGIN: 0cm 0cm 0pt&quot;>&lt;SPAN style=&quot;mso-ansi-language: EN-US&quot;>&lt;FONT size=3>&lt;FONT face=&quot;Times New Roman&quot;>The use of previous experience is also very important, because the identification of the architectural needs can be based on the results of previous projects.&lt;SPAN style=&quot;mso-spacerun: yes&quot;>&amp;nbsp; &lt;/SPAN>&lt;/FONT>&lt;/FONT>&lt;o:p>&lt;/o:p>&lt;/SPAN>&lt;/P>&#xD;
&lt;br/></sectionDescription>
  </sections>
  <sections xmi:id="_UBUgQMHrEd2B2LAvnwDruw" name="Define solutions and alternatives to fulfil needs  " guid="_UBUgQMHrEd2B2LAvnwDruw">
    <sectionDescription>&lt;P class=MsoNormal style=&quot;MARGIN: 0cm 0cm 0pt&quot;>&lt;SPAN style=&quot;mso-ansi-language: EN-US&quot;>&lt;FONT size=3>&lt;FONT face=&quot;Times New Roman&quot;>This step is to take that architectural needs and decide which architectural patterns, architecture models and policies are able to satisfy them. Depending on the problem the structure to solve it would be different. The solution is not going to be the same when the environment is very static and when the environment needs services flexibility (change the services, change functionalities in the services…). &lt;?xml:namespace prefix = o ns = &quot;urn:schemas-microsoft-com:office:office&quot; />&lt;o:p>&lt;/o:p>&lt;/FONT>&lt;/FONT>&lt;/SPAN>&lt;/P>&#xD;
&lt;P class=MsoNormal style=&quot;MARGIN: 0cm 0cm 0pt&quot;>&lt;SPAN style=&quot;mso-ansi-language: EN-US&quot;>&lt;FONT size=3>&lt;FONT face=&quot;Times New Roman&quot;>The best way to carry out this step is, first, identify possible skeletons (architectural patterns) to be the base of the solution, then those architecture solutions which implement the patterns and, finally, the policies which will complement the technical part of the architecture. &lt;o:p>&lt;/o:p>&lt;/FONT>&lt;/FONT>&lt;/SPAN>&lt;/P>&#xD;
&lt;P class=MsoNormal style=&quot;MARGIN: 0cm 0cm 0pt&quot;>&lt;SPAN style=&quot;mso-ansi-language: EN-US&quot;>&lt;FONT size=3>&lt;FONT face=&quot;Times New Roman&quot;>Have in mind strategic interests of the company to adequate alternatives. Some alternatives may be removed while others added due to the fact that the company does not want its engineers to use some architecture which could offer less performance. &lt;o:p>&lt;/o:p>&lt;/FONT>&lt;/FONT>&lt;/SPAN>&lt;/P>&#xD;
&lt;P class=MsoNormal style=&quot;MARGIN: 0cm 0cm 0pt&quot;>&lt;SPAN style=&quot;mso-ansi-language: EN-US&quot;>&lt;FONT size=3>&lt;FONT face=&quot;Times New Roman&quot;>To obtain a good result in this task, it is recommended to use previous or acquired knowledge (ESA, ERA, patterns and policies) when available. Put special attention in the information which explains for what type of problem a pattern is recommended or not. &lt;o:p>&lt;/o:p>&lt;/FONT>&lt;/FONT>&lt;/SPAN>&lt;/P>&#xD;
&lt;P class=MsoNormal style=&quot;MARGIN: 0cm 0cm 0pt&quot;>&lt;SPAN style=&quot;mso-ansi-language: EN-US&quot;>&lt;FONT size=3>&lt;FONT face=&quot;Times New Roman&quot;>SQUASH technique might be used to identify alternatives following a scenario based analysis. Even “define service sourcing policy” might help to pre-analyse possible decisions about services provisioning (develop or use third party services). &lt;o:p>&lt;/o:p>&lt;/FONT>&lt;/FONT>&lt;/SPAN>&lt;/P></sectionDescription>
  </sections>
